{
  "answer": "Vol I's primary treatment of indigenous occupation of land appears in chapter 11 (charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99, ch.11, para p-509527), where Comte acknowledges that European seizure of indigenous territories was 'evident usurpation' but sharply minimizes its significance: since the land had no cultivation-based value, the usurpation amounted to 'only the value of five centimes snatched away.' The 999/1000ths of current property value was legitimately created by industry, so the initial taking was trivial. Vol I also acknowledged in ch.7 that indigenous peoples have real national/tribal territorial rights (recognized and vigorously defended), and in ch.10 that the US government legitimately buys land from indigenous peoples before selling it to settlers.\n\nThe new wrinkle introduced in Vol II appears in chapter 44 (charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-ii-6beea5, ch.44, para p-011fbd): 'When a nation invades a territory occupied by another, and seizes its means of existence, the population placed on the same soil remains for a long time divided into two castes: that of the victors and that of the vanquished. If the former remains separated from the latter, not only by a difference of origin, but by differences of religion and laws, and by the measures it takes to prevent the descendants of the vanquished from becoming proprietors, the war continues between the two races.' Vol II ch.45 (para p-5de7c5) reinforces this by explicitly noting that this two-caste structure of total dispossession 'still exists among several nations of the American continent, and in most of the colonies that the moderns have founded.'\n\nWhat Vol I had been missing: Vol I evaluated indigenous occupation purely as an initial act of taking — and dismissed its moral weight by comparing the pre-cultivation value of the land to its post-cultivation value. It did not ask what happens structurally after the conquest. Vol II adds the crucial nuance that the real ongoing harm is not the value of the land at the moment of taking, but the systemic exclusion of the conquered population from ever becoming proprietors — a condition that perpetuates conflict indefinitely. The 'new wrinkle' is the shift from a one-time, backward-looking value calculation to a forward-looking structural analysis of how conquest creates permanent two-caste dispossession.",
